<dl id="n38134a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38134a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38134a"> 134(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ under articles <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n38134a"><li>FW 130.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n38134a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n38134a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n38134a">MS BL 47475-271</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:264 <a name="fad6y" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#fad6y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad6.htm#n38134a">Draft: I.6&sect;1.6</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Michael Arne (1741-86) <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> was the composer of many songs, and pieces for the harpsichord, on which instrument he was a skilled executant. The younger Arne died in great destitution, for he was of a dreamy, shiftless nature. Kelly stated that &ldquo;Arne, not content with being one of the greatest musical geniuses the world ever produced, wished also to possess the philosopher&apos;s stone; and, fancying himself a great alchemist, actually took a house at Richmond, near Dublin, and, neglecting all his pupils, gave himself up to a scientific search for gold. The consequences were ruin and a spunging-house. He was <mark>under articles</mark> to compose an opera for Covent Garden; and, my father, knowing this, sent him, in his confinement, a pianoforte <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>&rdquo; <small> S.M. Ellis, <a name="ELMK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ELMK"><cite title="source">The Life of Michael Kelly</cite></a>,(1930) 22n1</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
